reviewText: To start, if your easily insulted...or even semi-easily insulted, this one isn't for you. You have to be able to see the humor in just about everything to like Tosh's stand up. His unique in how one joke always flows into the next, yet there's no real story to his lines. He's not up on stage telling about something funny that happened to him on his way to the airport. His lines come off like that sarcastic friend who's always off in his own head thinking about something else entirely than what is currently the topic at hand.His comedy will offend every kind of group out there, and that's pretty much the point. His jokes are meant to shock and cause you to laugh at all the things you know you're not supposed to. There is nothing in this film appropriate for kids of any age. He swears and talk about things that would make a porn star blush.What I like about his stand up show over his TV show is this is all his material and there's no videos of anyone doing anything sick on YouTube. I think Tosh is hysterical, but I can't watch Tosh.0 because of the America's Funniest Home Videos rejects clips he shows. Half of them make you want to gag or at least ruin the idea of eating anything for the rest of the day. So if you think Tosh.0 is funny, you're going to love his stand up show.

reviewText: Oh Daniel Tosh- this man is a comedic genesis and is well-before his time. His jokes are short and witty and make me absolutely crack up.  We have watched this dvd several times and I laugh at the same parts each and every time.  Tosh's delivery is phenomenal.I like to think that his comedy is for the intellectually savy. Most of his jokes start out hitting a large % of the audience and as he goes on less of the audience is following him until there is a small % of people that are still cracking up! Some of his jokes are intellectually hilarious while others are the run of the mill ethnocentric based humor.I recommend this full length dvd to anyone who saw clips of Tosh on comedy central or other stand up spotlights on the artist- Worth the buck! Money can't buy happiness but it can buy an hour worth of laughter-

reviewText: One of the major drawbacks in purchasing recordings of comedy performances is the durability of the material to make it worthwhile coming back to watch again and again. Now after numerous viewings of the '07 DVD `Daniel Tosh: Completely Serious' I must say that it continues to delight and entertain. Is it his contagious boyish grin, expressive facial features or relentless comedic routines that bring me back again and again?I'm certain it's all the above plus his nothing sacred, everything fair game attitude which is cleverly balanced by his nave unassuming demeanor, faux sincerity and Orange County good looks. It takes nothing more than a well placed cheshire grin to persuade his audience to forgive his politically/socially incorrect forays into; race, religion, God, death, plastic surgery and dwarfish.This one is funny from beginning to end and great to have at your fingertips whenever you're in need of a good laugh!
summary: "I'll Feed You Baby Birds ~ More Of A Prophet, Less Of A Comedian"

reviewText: This may be my favorite comedy album (DVD whatever) of all time. I have watched this over, and over and just laugh my ass off every time I play it. Tosh just has a way of putting forth jokes so quickly and to the point. Its like condensed comedy. Also, he is very blue and pokes  fun at all racial stereotypes, etc. But the difference between a racist joke and a non racist joke is this; "is it funny". The answer is an overwhelming, yes.But, if you can't take blue humor or jokes on the edge of civility (well mostly well outside of it) then you should skip it. But if you want funny, Daniel Tosh brings it in abundance.  This show is a non-stop onslaught of smart humor. You just have to "get it".  Many do, but some will not. Too bad for them because if you want your stomach to hurt from laughing, get this Blu-ray/DVD/MP3 however you do.

reviewText: As a fan of Tosh.0, this was a huge disappointment. I didn't realize this was made in 2007 until after viewing - here, Tosh lacks his fluidity and self confidence and seems somewhat nervous and out of place on the stage. He has trouble linking the material and some of the more offensive jokes - usually handled with a trademark panache in his TV show - come across as deliberately provocative without being able to extract the humor.The second half of the performance is significantly stronger than the first but by then you're not expecting the show to recover. I can only presume that he's discovered and perfected his style on the TV show where I tend to find most of his material very funny but this stand-up performance is definitely one to skip.
summary: Not up to the Tosh.0 standard

reviewText: Daniel Tosh is funny for a few minutes, then it gets old.. It's like that one relative who doesn't know when to shut up and go away.. Yeah, he's "unfiltered", but so is a kid in special ed, or a senile old man. He lists all of his favorite idols, of which he will never be. His routines have no direction, only the punch line which is anyone with a pulse.  Louie CK and Carlin are comic geniuses.. Tosh is just the bell boy asked to bring up the rest of their luggage.. When Louie and Carlin performed they were passionate while having humility.. Tosh is more of a sociopath who says things, not because it's an observation that needs to be said, but because it's something that will get a scoff. Dice Clay was like that too, although Clay managed a few rhymes here and there... Then again, where is Dice Clay these days?? Exactly..

reviewText: I'll start by saying I really like comedy. I have well over 200 comedy CDs and DVDs from Abbott and Costello to Lenny Bruce to Steve Martin to David Cross (oops!) to guys stumping the clubs today.If you listen to a lot of comedy, you get a feeling for who has put in the work to really polish their material, and for who has a unique and compelling voice. Tosh has worked this material to perfection; the timing is spot on, the delivery is expert, and he works the line that has you squirming AND laughing.For me, "Completely Serious" has to be one of the ten best comedy albums ever. OK, it's a DVD, but I ripped the soundtrack and listen to it on my portable music player. Its software tells me I've heard the album 55 times. I've played the video at least a half dozen times.I recommend this to anyone who's willing to laugh at taboo subjects. If you're familiar with Louis C.K., I'd say the "willing to offend" meter deflects similarly for the two, though they are otherwise quite different. If you're at all easily offended, this is not for you. Otherwise, buckle up. You're in for a treat.Since CDs come with track lists but DVDs don't, I'm going to list the first dozen of the 27 "tracks" I got from ripping the DVD. This might give you an idea of whether you'll like this set:1) Intro / The O.C. / How Much Longer Do I Have?2) Swearing in Heaven / Ashton Kutcher is a D*****bag3) Banging Teachers4) Snapple Knowledge5) Seal the Border6) Is Poker a Sport?7) Bring the Troops Home (to War in Nebraska)8) Parade or Fireworks?9) Happiness Through Material Possessions10) I'm Not Honest (But You're Interesting) / Stupid Wh**es and Plastic Surgery11) The Myth of the Hot Female Athlete12) The Polite Version of Tourette's
summary: One of my favorite comedy albums ever

reviewText: 4.8 starsBy far the best stand-up performance I've seen since Chris Rock's perfect Bigger And Blacker, this is one hour of extremely edgy yet somehow good-natured comedy. Tosh spares nothing and no one, least of all America in general. And he does it all so slyly, with that engaging grin and flashing eyes that say, yeah, you know I'm right, admit it.The material here is twenty minutes longer than what the Comedy Chunnel shows from this dvd. They cut a lot of the best, most over the top bits, so it's a treat to see them here. What really distinguishes Tosh is the intelligence and subtlety of some of his lines. He's skewering all of us, and our selfish society, and does it with so much verve and bonhomie that you hardly notice how deep the cuts go.I enjoy a comedian who can get straight to the heart of things, and Tosh is a master at that already on his first dvd. He's one of the few stand-ups I've seen in years who clearly has the goods in spades, and seems more interested in commenting on his version of the truth than getting easy laughs. He says things that seem so wrong at first, but one quickly realizes what's really wrong is how right he is about our complacency and prejudices.His new show on CC, Tosh.0, is decent, but goes for easy laughs and is nowhere near as funny as this dvd and his earlier cd. Let's hope the tv stardom doesn't derail his excellent stand-up, and that he doesn't go the Rock route and release only one performance every five years. Truth is at a premium these days, and this guy is poised to be a prime conduit.Absolutely recommended to any fan of Carlin, Pryor, Hicks, or Rock.

reviewText: Daniel Tosh is one of the most hilarious and underrated comedians in the past few years, not to mention pretty dang adorable.This hour long video will have you laughing til it hurts and then a little bit more. It covers a lot of his older material and some of the classics! Of course, perhaps not for everyone, ("Is this a comedy club? I hope there will be jokes and sarcasm!") but for the witty and intellectual it is a sure crack-up.Repeat viewings only make it better and better, his expression and demeanor carry his jokes onto a whole different level. Pure genius!"Sometimes, when I'm feeling down because nothing seems to be going right, I like to take a home pregnancy test. Then I can say, 'Hey, at least I'm not pregnant."If you've ever seen him live as I have, you know this guy is a non-stop riot and he's got lots more from where this came from!Think: Dane Cook meets Jim Gaffigan, they have a baby, and the baby reads.  Thank you Daniel Tosh!
summary: "I'm not relgious, but I'm spiritual." I like to reply, "I'm not honest, but you're interesting."
